Part 1

Winter, 1996/97.

Second year MBBS.

Six months into second year.

Evening.

Adarsh knocked on Vikram's door.

No answer.

He pushed it open.

Empty.

Textbooks open on the desk.

Pathology.

Half-underlined.

Tea gone cold in a steel tumbler.

Full tumbler.

Vikram never left tea unfinished.

Not once in six months.

Adarsh noticed that before he noticed anything else.

Adarsh checked the corridor.

Nothing.

He walked down towards the warden's office.

There was one phone in the hostel.

Black.

Rotary dial.

Chained to the wall outside the warden's room.

Everyone used it.

Everyone waited in line for it.

Tonight there was no line.

Just Vikram.

Standing.

Receiver against his ear.

Not speaking.

Just listening.

Adarsh slowed down.

Something in the way Vikram stood.

Shoulders too still.

Adarsh didn't go closer.

Waited near the stairs.

"...

when?"

Vikram's voice.

Barely audible.

The line crackled.

Trunk call, routed through two exchanges, the operator's voice cutting in once — "Connected, go ahead" — then static.

"...

how bad?"

The line went dead mid-sentence.

Vikram stood there, receiver still pressed to his ear, listening to nothing.

Then dialled again.

Got through.

"...

say it again."

Silence.

Then.

"I'm coming.

Tonight."

He put the receiver down.

Didn't move.

Stood there.

Staring at the wall in front of him.

The bulb above the phone flickered.

Buzzed.

Steadied again.

Adarsh walked over.

"Vicky?"

No response.

"Vicky."

Vikram turned.

His face...

Adarsh had never seen it like that.

Not sad exactly.

Emptied.

"Papa."

He stopped there.

Adarsh waited.

"They said liver.

Then they said a word I made him repeat twice."

"What word?"

"Decompensated."

Adarsh felt his own stomach drop.

He knew the word.

Pathology, third chapter, the one neither of them had properly finished.

"That doesn't mean—"

"I know what it means and what it doesn't."

Vikram's voice was flat.

"It means nobody can tell me yet if he has one bad month or five good years.

Uncle just kept saying 'we'll see, we'll see.'

I've never heard a doctor sound more useless."

Adarsh didn't know what to say.

Nobody teaches you what to say.

Not even in a medical college.

"I need to go home."

"I'll come with—"

"No."

Too fast.

Vikram softened it.

"No.

Stay.

Exams are close.

I'll go alone."

"Vicky, this isn't about exams—"

"I know what it's about."

Sharp.

Then immediately, quieter.

"Sorry."

Adarsh said nothing.

Followed him back to the room.

Vikram pulled out a bag.

Started throwing things in.

Two shirts.

Then his hand went to the shelf.

Stopped at the dissection kit.

Small steel instruments, wrapped in cloth, the ones he'd kept wound tight and oiled since first year.

He almost packed it.

Didn't.

Put it back exactly where it was, like leaving a place for something to return to.

Then he looked at the desk.

Pathology textbook.

Half-underlined.

He picked it up.

Held it for a second.

Put it back down.

Didn't pack it.

Adarsh noticed.

Said nothing.

Vikram zipped the bag.

Looked around the room once.

As if checking he wasn't forgetting something.

He was forgetting nothing.

He was leaving something.

"There's a train at 11," he said.

"I'll make it if I leave now."

Adarsh walked him to the gate.

Night had settled fully.

Crickets somewhere.

A stray dog followed them halfway, then lost interest.

At the gate, Vikram stopped.

Turned to Adarsh.

"If I don't come back for the practical exam—"

"You'll come back."

"If I don't—"

"Vicky."

Vikram exhaled.

"Papa always wanted a doctor in the family.

He used to tell relatives.

'My son will wear the white coat.'

Proudly.

Like it was already done."

He looked at his hands.

"I don't think that's happening now."

"Don't decide anything tonight."

"I'm not deciding.

I'm just telling you what I already know."

A rickshaw turned in at the hostel gate, headlights sweeping across them.

Vikram picked up his bag.

"Tell the professor.

Family emergency.

I'll write when I know more."

"Vicky—"

He was already walking towards the rickshaw.

Half-turned back.

"Thanks for not asking if I'm okay."

Adarsh hadn't even thought to ask.

Some questions you don't ask a man carrying a bag at 10 PM because his father might be dying, or might not, and nobody will say which for weeks.

The rickshaw pulled away.

Red tail-light shrinking down the dark road.

Adarsh stood at the gate a long time.

Then walked back to Vikram's room.

The door was still open.

He looked at the desk.

Pathology textbook.

Half-underlined.

Left behind.

He picked it up.

Closed it.

Kept it safely in the cupboard.

Waiting for a return that would take twenty-two years.

---

Vikram never came back for the practical exam.

Or the next semester.

Or the one after.

The name stayed on the college register for one more year.

Struck off eventually.

Nobody in the hostel talked about it for long.

New batch arrived.

New rumors replaced old ones.

Adarsh kept the pathology textbook for a while.

Then, packing to leave hostel himself years later, he found it again.

Half-underlined.

Dust on the cover.

He didn't know where to send it.

He never found out the address.

He kept it anyway.

Every year, around the same winter week, he'd open that cupboard and find it still there.

Dust a little thicker.

He never asked himself why he hadn't thrown it out.

He just closed the cupboard again.
